This paper deals with the performance analysis of WLANs operating under Dynamic Channel Bonding (DCB) in dense networks. The paper focuses on the interactions between adjacent WLANs with overlapping channels, which falls under the category of networked systems (cs.NI). The paper also uses a Markov chain model to analyze the performance, which is a common technique in information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper discusses the impact of larger bandwidths on contention and throughput, which is related to multimedia systems (cs.MM) and social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper considers the security implications of DCB networks, which falls under the category of cryptography and security (cs.CR).
